The <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> and the <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span> have broken with Brüning, voting against the act when it came to a vote in the Reichstag. However, this decision has ignited fierce internal divisions within both parties. A significant pro-Brüning faction—including figures like Westarp, Curtius, and several influential industrialists such as Hans Luther—pushed for continued support, convincing a sizable minority in both parties to back the act as the bitter medicine for Germany’s economic woes.

Despite these divisions, when the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> introduced a vote of no confidence, defectors from both parties tipped the scales, narrowly bringing down Brüning’s government. New elections have been scheduled for [+ next_election_month : month +] [+ next_election_year +].

