A significant portion of the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> and <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span>'s Reichstag delegations initially pushed to break with Brüning, threatening to vote against the act. This sparked fierce internal divisions within both parties, as a strong pro-Brüning faction—including figures like Westarp, Curtius, and several influential industrialists such as Hans Luther—argued for continued support, persuading their colleagues to back the act as a necessary, albeit painful, remedy for Germany’s economic woes.

As a result, the planned vote of no confidence has been shelved, allowing the bourgeois-right government to survive—albeit with its unity hanging by a thread.

